Your economic and political failure was largely due to actively supported secessionist movements from Russia, which sought to keep both countries within the "influence sphere" of the Kremlin.
When bloody conflicts erupted in Transnistria, Abkhazia, and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence there into "peacekeeping forces" to maintain control.
For a long time, it was feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly turn into hot ones.
Not only has this not happened, but we can now speak of solutions – for both Georgia and Moldova have begun to achieve breakthroughs towards a market economy and democracy.
To that, the "Neighbourhood Policy" of the European Union has also contributed.
The starting point of these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years prior.
Already dangerously close to a failed state, Georgia has since turned towards the West.
The success of various "color revolutions" in former Soviet bloc countries also triggered a transformation in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms whose goal is to bring Moldova closer to the EU.
These changes have triggered new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova aimed at restoring the territorial integrity of these countries in a peaceful manner.
The experience of Estonia suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policies toward Russia.
When Estonia became independent in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as a country with enormous economic problems that was unsuitable for investment.
Estonia was indeed poor, and its most important export products were scrap metal and wood, but its economy was growing.
In North-East Estonia, which has a predominantly Russian-speaking population that had settled there during the Soviet era, Russia supported what is known as an "autonomy movement."
When Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and interrupted gas supplies.
High taxes were levied on the few Estonian products that were allowed to be imported into Russia, and Russia even threatened with a military intervention.
But Estonia stayed calm.
The Russian sanctions helped the country even in reorienting its economy towards the West.
On the other hand, West Europe did what it could to integrate the Baltic States – Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia – and at the same time tried to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, a free trade agreement with the EU enabled Estonian products to find new markets, and as a result, Estonia ultimately became one of the most successful post-communist transition countries, joining both the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia became independent in 1991, it was not supported to the same extent by Western Europe.
Of course, Georgia appeared as a partner less attractive than the Baltic states; the 1990s were characterized by coups, counter-coups, and civil wars, during which two regions – Abkhazia and South Ossetia – essentially separated with the support of Russia.
The country has done its best to make its bleak past fade from memory.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army strengthened, and the leadership of the country is young, dynamic, and diligently working to advance the nation.
Thanks to Georgia's flat income tax of 12% – which is likely the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has increased pensions and raised social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a judicial reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and by more than 10% in 2006.
Georgia is trying to defuse tensions over Abkhazia and South Ossetia; Russia, however, accuses the country of aggression as well as ethnic cleansing.
His main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and to hinder reconciliation with the breakaway regions.
The powers that matter for Georgia are Russia and to a certain extent the United States.
Europe must show that it is likewise important.
Estonia has shown, during both its independence and most recently during the crisis over the relocation of a Soviet-era monument, that it is possible to resist Russian pressure with determination and strong support.
Europe must understand that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe has enabled Estonia to find new markets, this could be the means by which Georgians can help themselves.
Georgia has legitimate reason for hope that it will achieve true independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is more threatened by Russia than the Estonians or even the Georgians were at their most vulnerable moments?
The missing reform successes are partly the result of secessionist movements supported by Russia.
That industrialized region of Transnistria, whose Russian- and Ukrainian-speaking population, mainly Moldovans of Romanian origin, feared closer ties with Romania, seceded from Moldova, dealt the independence of the country a severe blow right from the start.
A civil war ensued, and in 1992 Russian troops marched into Transnistria, where they are still stationed today.
The independence of Transnistria was never recognized – neither by Moldova nor internationally.
It is said that there is lawlessness and corruption there.
The Czech Republic is highly indebted, unemployment is high, and its once renowned wine industry is in decline.
Russia occasionally cuts gas supplies, and many of the four million residents have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Representatives of Moldova have undertaken four fruitless visits to Moscow to persuade President Vladimir Putin to engage in finding a solution and to withdraw Russian troops.
A desperate Voronin appealed to the EU observation team Eubam for help, but an EU initiative would require Russian cooperation.
Unfortunately, it seems that the West is lacking up-to-date insights into the situation in Moldova.
For example, in April, the EU and also the USA learned about a proposed peace agreement for the first time through a report that leaked from Germany.
This would seem to favor Russia, as it recognizes Transnistria as a legitimate entity within Moldova.
If Russia has stabbed the West in the back in this manner, it would be an ominous precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
